Anonymous Tue 26 Feb 2019 18:47:05 No.21550559 Report
Quoted By: >>21550741
>>21550312
When you think about it there are essentially 3 core schools of thought when it comes to drawing anthro muzzles.

1: Just do it exactly like the real animal.
This is the prefered style of the people who draw realistic anthros (duh).
2: keep a largely human head but modify just the maxilla to be that of an animals, making some concessions to have ti fit with the human lower jaw.
This is what a lot of kemono artists tend to do
3: Take a human head and project the maxilla and lower jaw forward to form a sort of pseudo muzzle, then add the missing detail.
This is basically what a lot of more "toony" furry designs do.

Of course, these are just vague categorizations that I made up, nothing firs into them perfectly. What you posted, for example, is a mix of approach 2 and 3.
It's just a way of thinking of how to approach muzzles.
